    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-22T01:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-22T01:30:00-05:00" n="181"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">390.1115A/651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Bombay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bombay</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-22T13:00:00+06:30"
                            >January 22, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 22—5:36 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. In arranging for passages to the United States for American citizens and
                    families, steamship companies object to taking alien wives without reasonable
                    assurance of their admissibility particularly when wives are enemy subjects.
                    Would alien enemy wives be refused admission solely because of nationality
                    status?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Donovan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
